      "source": "Great üëç\nThis section builds on enums and shows **two very important ideas**:\n\n1. **Using enums in `switch` statements (modern Java syntax)**\n2. **Enums with behavior (methods inside enums)**\n\nI‚Äôll explain **each file**, then tie everything together with best practices.\n\n---\n\n# üìÅ File 1: `DayOfTheWeek.java`\n\n```java\npublic enum DayOfTheWeek {\n    SUN, MON, TUES, WED, THURS, FRI, SAT\n}\n```\n\nNothing new here structurally, but remember:\n\n* This defines **7 fixed instances**\n* Each constant is a **singleton**\n* Order matters for `ordinal()` (but don‚Äôt rely on it for logic)\n\n---\n\n# üìÅ File 2: `Main.java`\n\n---\n\n## 1Ô∏è‚É£ Assigning and printing an enum\n\n```java\nDayOfTheWeek weekDay = DayOfTheWeek.TUES;\nSystem.out.println(weekDay);\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\nTUES\n```\n\nWhy?\n\n* Default `toString()` of enum prints the constant name\n\n---\n\n## 2Ô∏è‚É£ Loop with random enum values\n\n```java\nfor (int i = 0; i < 10; i++ ) {\n    weekDay = getRandomDay();\n    switchDayOfWeek(weekDay);\n}\n```\n\nEach iteration:\n\n* Picks a random `DayOfTheWeek`\n* Passes it into a method that uses a `switch`\n\n---\n\n## 3Ô∏è‚É£ `switchDayOfWeek` ‚Äî ENUM + SWITCH (CORE LESSON)\n\n```java\npublic static void switchDayOfWeek(DayOfTheWeek weekDay) {\n```\n\n### Calculating a ‚Äúday number‚Äù\n\n```java\nint weekDayInteger = weekDay.ordinal() + 1;\n```\n\n* `ordinal()` ‚Üí position starting from `0`\n* `+1` ‚Üí makes it human-friendly (1‚Äì7)\n\n‚ö†Ô∏è **Important warning**\nThis is okay for demos, but **don‚Äôt use `ordinal()` for real business logic**, because changing enum order breaks behavior.\n\n---\n\n## 4Ô∏è‚É£ Modern switch expression (Java 14+ style)\n\n```java\nswitch (weekDay) {\n    case WED -> System.out.println(\"Wednesday is Day \" + weekDayInteger);\n    case SAT -> System.out.println(\"Saturday is Day \" + weekDayInteger);\n    default -> System.out.println(\n        weekDay.name().charAt(0) +\n        weekDay.name().substring(1).toLowerCase() +\n        \"day is Day \" + weekDayInteger\n    );\n}\n```\n\n### What‚Äôs happening\n\n* `switch` works **directly with enums**\n* No `break` statements needed (`->` syntax)\n* Compiler ensures **all enum cases are covered**\n\n---\n\n### Why only `WED` and `SAT` are explicit\n\n* Those days have special formatting\n* All others fall into `default`\n\nExample output:\n\n```\nWednesday is Day 4\nFriday is Day 6\nSunday is Day 1\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5Ô∏è‚É£ Formatting enum names nicely\n\n```java\nweekDay.name().charAt(0) +\nweekDay.name().substring(1).toLowerCase()\n```\n\nIf `weekDay.name()` is `\"FRI\"`:\n\nSteps:\n\n* `charAt(0)` ‚Üí `'F'`\n* `substring(1)` ‚Üí `\"RI\"`\n* `.toLowerCase()` ‚Üí `\"ri\"`\n\nResult:\n\n```\n\"Fri\"\n```\n\nThen `\"day\"` is appended ‚Üí `\"Friday\"`\n\n---\n\n## 6Ô∏è‚É£ Getting a random enum value\n\n```java\npublic static DayOfTheWeek getRandomDay() {\n    int randomInteger = new Random().nextInt(7);\n    var allDays = DayOfTheWeek.values();\n    return allDays[randomInteger];\n}\n```\n\nKey points:\n\n* `values()` returns `DayOfTheWeek[]`\n* Random index picks a random enum constant\n\n‚úÖ Safer version:\n\n```java\nnew Random().nextInt(DayOfTheWeek.values().length);\n```\n\n---\n\n## 7Ô∏è‚É£ Iterating over another enum: `Topping`\n\n```java\nfor (Topping topping : Topping.values()) {\n    System.out.println(topping.name() + \" : \" + topping.getPrice());\n}\n```\n\n* `values()` lets you loop over **all enum constants**\n* Each enum constant can have **behavior**\n\n---\n\n# üìÅ File 3: `Topping.java` (ENUM WITH METHODS)\n\n```java\npublic enum Topping {\n    MUSTARD,\n    PICKLES,\n    BACON,\n    CHEDDAR,\n    TOMATO;\n```\n\nThis enum represents **burger toppings**.\n\n---\n\n## 8Ô∏è‚É£ Enum with behavior (VERY IMPORTANT)\n\n```java\npublic double getPrice() {\n    return switch (this) {\n        case BACON -> 1.5;\n        case CHEDDAR -> 1.0;\n        default -> 0.0;\n    };\n}\n```\n\n### Key ideas\n\n* Enums can have **methods**\n* `this` refers to the **current enum constant**\n* Each constant can behave differently\n\nExample:\n\n```java\nTopping.BACON.getPrice();   // 1.5\nTopping.MUSTARD.getPrice(); // 0.0\n```\n\n---\n\n## 9Ô∏è‚É£ Why this is powerful\n\nEnums are not just constants ‚Äî they are **full classes**.\n\nInstead of:\n\n```java\nif (topping == BACON) price = 1.5;\n```\n\nYou write:\n\n```java\nprice = topping.getPrice();\n```\n\n‚úî Cleaner\n‚úî Object-oriented\n‚úî Easier to maintain\n\n---\n\n# üß† Mental model for enums + switch\n\n* Enums are **types**, not numbers\n* `switch` understands enums natively\n* Modern switch (`->`) is safer and clearer\n* Enums can hold **logic**, not just values\n\n---\n\n# ‚ö†Ô∏è Best practices (VERY IMPORTANT)\n\n### ‚úÖ Do\n\n* Use enums in `switch`\n* Use `==` to compare enums\n* Put related behavior inside enums\n\n### ‚ùå Avoid\n\n* Using `ordinal()` for logic\n* Using `String` instead of enums\n* Large `if-else` chains for enum behavior\n\n---\n\n# üéØ Final takeaway\n\nThis section teaches you:\n\n‚úî Enums in `switch` statements\n‚úî Modern switch syntax\n‚úî Enum methods & behavior\n‚úî Cleaner, safer design patterns\n\nYou‚Äôre now using enums the **right way**, like real-world Java code üëç\n\nIf you want next, I can explain:\n\n1. Enums with fields + constructors\n2. Strategy pattern using enums\n3. EnumMap / EnumSet\n4. When enums beat constants\n\nJust tell me üòä\n",
